  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a widespread and clear consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity in virtually every country and jurisdiction around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or other criminal acts) appear legitimate by passing it through complex transactions or financial systems.\n\nMost countries have established laws and regulations specifically targeting money laundering, often in compliance with international standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which is a global watchdog for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. Additionally, many countries have signed treaties and agreements to cooperate in combating money laundering across borders.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally illegal and is actively prosecuted by law enforcement agencies worldwide.",
